WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Welcome to Introduction to Machine Learning. I'm Dr. Sarah Chen.

00:00:05.200 --> 00:00:11.000
Today we'll cover the fundamental concepts that underpin all of modern AI.

00:00:11.500 --> 00:00:17.000
Machine learning is the science of getting computers to act without being explicitly programmed.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:24.000
Instead of writing rules by hand, we feed data to algorithms and let them learn patterns.

00:00:24.500 --> 00:00:31.000
There are three main paradigms: supervised learning, unsupervised learning, and reinforcement learning.

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:38.000
In supervised learning, we train a model on labeled examples — input-output pairs.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:45.000
The model learns a mapping from inputs to outputs that generalizes to new, unseen data.

00:00:45.500 --> 00:00:52.000
Classic examples include spam detection, image classification, and price prediction.

00:00:52.500 --> 00:01:00.000
Unsupervised learning deals with unlabeled data — finding hidden structure without guidance.

00:01:00.500 --> 00:01:08.000
Clustering algorithms like k-means group similar data points together based on distance metrics.

00:01:08.500 --> 00:01:16.000
Dimensionality reduction techniques like PCA compress data while preserving its essential variance.

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:24.000
Reinforcement learning is inspired by how animals learn through reward and punishment.

00:01:24.500 --> 00:01:32.000
An agent takes actions in an environment and receives rewards or penalties based on outcomes.

00:01:32.500 --> 00:01:40.000
Over many iterations, the agent learns a policy that maximizes cumulative reward.

00:01:40.500 --> 00:01:48.000
AlphaGo and modern game-playing AIs are famous examples of reinforcement learning at scale.

00:01:48.500 --> 00:01:56.000
Let's talk about the bias-variance tradeoff — one of the most important concepts in ML.

00:01:56.500 --> 00:02:04.000
Bias is error from overly simplistic assumptions. A high-bias model underfits the data.

00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:12.000
Variance is error from sensitivity to fluctuations in training data. High variance means overfitting.

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:20.000
The goal is to find a sweet spot — a model complex enough to capture patterns but not noise.

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:28.000
Cross-validation is our primary tool for estimating how well a model generalizes.

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:36.000
We split data into folds, train on some, evaluate on others, and average the results.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:44.000
Feature engineering is the process of transforming raw data into representations useful for learning.

00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:52.000
Good features encode domain knowledge and often matter more than algorithm choice.

00:02:52.500 --> 00:03:00.000
Normalization and standardization ensure features with different scales don't dominate the model.

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:08.000
Now let's discuss gradient descent — the optimization engine behind most ML algorithms.

00:03:08.500 --> 00:03:16.000
We define a loss function that measures how wrong our model's predictions are.

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:24.000
Gradient descent iteratively adjusts parameters to move downhill on the loss surface.

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:32.000
The learning rate controls the step size. Too large and we overshoot; too small and training is slow.

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:40.000
Stochastic gradient descent uses random mini-batches, which adds noise but speeds up convergence.

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:48.000
Modern optimizers like Adam adapt the learning rate per parameter using momentum estimates.

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:56.000
To summarize: ML is about learning patterns from data using algorithms that generalize.

00:03:56.500 --> 00:04:04.000
Next week we'll dive into linear regression and logistic regression as foundational supervised models.

00:04:04.500 --> 00:04:10.000
Please complete the assigned readings on chapters 2 and 3 before then. See you next time.
